      • getMonitor

        public AsynchronousLatencyMonitor getMonitor(java.lang.String workCategory)
        Description copied from interface: MonitorFactory

        Returns the monitor for the given category of work.

        In the case where the specified category has not been configured explicitly, this method will create an implicit statistical requirement for the category. It will also associate a basic alerts logger to the requirement, prior to returning a monitor for it.

        This call is not required to create a brand new monitor with each invocation. It is feasible that where a monitor already exists for the given category, this method will simply return a reference to it rather than creating a fresh one.

        Specified by:
        getMonitor in interface MonitorFactory
        Parameters:
        workCategory - The category of work for which the monitor is being returned.
        Returns:
        A monitor initialised to observe the requirement (implicit or explicit) which governs the given workCategory.

      • init

        public void init()

        Initialises this factory. In doing so, this method will attempt to read the Latency4J configuration from the first available of the following three choices:

        • The configuration path specified for this instance.
        • Or the value of the vm property Latency4JConstants.CONFIG_FILE_VM_PROP.
        • If the above two options are not available, it will search for the file Latency4JConstants.DEFAULT_CONFIGURATION_RESOURCE_NAME in the application classpath.

      • init

        public void init(java.io.InputStream stream)

        Forces initialisation from the configuration which is read from the given stream. Provided as an alternative to the init() method, and for situations where it is necessary to override the configuration from a specific stream.

        Parameters:
